{
  "texts": [
    "Second, it gives no insight into the kinds of social learning mechanisms that support cultural transmission (Sterelny, 2009; Acerbi et al., 2022).",
    "This criticism is important because some higher fidelity social learning processes, such as imitation (aka 'process copying ' Buskell & Tennie, 2022, or 'know-how copying' Tennie, 2023), are thought to play an important (if not always necessary) role in the emergence of cumulative culture (Tennie et al., 2009; Moore, 2013).",
    "These may be missing in other species, or too inconsequential to produce and maintain similar cultures.",
    "Tennie and colleagues have developed a series of paradigms designed to test whether putatively cultural behaviours in our nearest relatives, the great apes, are a product of imitation.",
    "Early paradigms established that chimpanzees do not acquire behaviours whose transmission requires high-fidelity transmission chains (Tennie et al., 2009)."
  ]
}